True Cache vs Active Data Guard Standby — Step Comparison
True Cache setup is deliberately modelled on Physical Standby setup — the prerequisites and redo transport wiring are almost identical. This section maps every standby step to its True Cache equivalent so experienced DBA standby builders can ramp up instantly.

Green = identical step  |  Amber = similar but different  |  Red = not needed in True Cache  |  Blue = True Cache only

#	Step	Match	Active Data Guard Standby	True Cache
On PRIMARY — prepare the source database
1	ARCHIVELOG mode	Identical	Required. ALTER DATABASE ARCHIVELOG;	Required. Same command, no difference.
2	FORCE LOGGING	Identical	Required. ALTER DATABASE FORCE LOGGING;	Required. Same command.
3	DB_UNIQUE_NAME	Identical	Set on primary SPFILE. e.g. PRODDB	Same requirement, same parameter.
4	Standby redo logs on primary	Different	Required for fast failover. ALTER DATABASE ADD STANDBY LOGFILE …	Not required. True Cache does not use standby redo logs.
5	LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST_n	Identical	SERVICE= pointing to standby, ASYNC or SYNC.	Same syntax — SERVICE= pointing to True Cache.
6	LOG_ARCHIVE_CONFIG DG_CONFIG	Identical	DG_CONFIG=(PRODDB,STANDBY1)	DG_CONFIG=(PRODDB,TRUECACHE1). Same syntax.
7	Password file	Identical	orapwd on primary, scp to standby host.	Same — scp orapw file to True Cache host.
8	TNS entries	Identical	Add standby TNS alias in primary tnsnames.ora.	Add True Cache TNS alias. Same format.
On STANDBY / TRUE CACHE HOST — create the instance
9	Oracle software install	Identical	Same Oracle version + patches as primary.	Same — same version, same patches.
10	RMAN backup / restore	Not needed	Required. RMAN DUPLICATE FROM ACTIVE DATABASE to seed standby datafiles. Time-consuming.	NOT needed. No datafiles. Buffer cache built lazily on first query from primary.
11	Standby redo logs on standby	Not needed	Required. Must match primary log size, count +1 group per thread.	NOT needed. Skipped entirely.
12	init.ora / SPFILE	Different	Standard params: DB_UNIQUE_NAME, FAL_SERVER, LOG_ARCHIVE_DEST, DB_FILE_NAME_CONVERT.	Must include TRUE_CACHE=TRUE. No DB_FILE_NAME_CONVERT. Focus on SGA_TARGET.
13	Instance creation method	Different	STARTUP NOMOUNT + RMAN DUPLICATE, or DBCA duplicate wizard.	dbca -createTrueCache — one command, no RMAN step.
14	Redo Apply startup	Different	ALTER DATABASE RECOVER MANAGED STANDBY DATABASE DISCONNECT FROM SESSION;	Started automatically by DBCA. No manual command needed.
15	Open database	Different	ALTER DATABASE OPEN READ ONLY; then start MRP process.	DBCA handles this. Opens automatically in READ ONLY WITH APPLY mode.
Service & application configuration
16	Read service creation	Different	DBMS_SERVICE.CREATE_SERVICE with standard params. App must explicitly use standby URL.	DBMS_SERVICE.CREATE_SERVICE with TRUE_CACHE_SERVICE param. JDBC auto-routes.
17	Application changes required	Different	App needs separate connection pool or URL for standby reads. Code change often needed.	Zero application changes. JDBC thin driver auto-routes read-only transactions.
18	True Cache only — hit ratio monitoring	TC only	Not applicable.	Monitor V$TRUE_CACHE_STATS — TRUE_CACHE_HIT_RATIO target > 80%.
Ongoing management differences
19	Failover / switchover	Different	Full Data Guard failover and switchover. Can become primary.	No failover. Read-offload only. Cannot become primary.
20	Disk storage to manage	Different	Full ASM disk group — same size as primary. Monitor space, RMAN backups.	No disk. Monitor SGA/buffer cache hit ratio and memory pressure only.
21	RMAN backups on standby	Different	Common pattern — offload RMAN backups to standby to reduce primary I/O.	No backups. True Cache holds no persistent data.
22	Apply lag monitoring	Identical	V$DATAGUARD_STATS — apply lag, transport lag.	Same views. Same alert thresholds.

At a glance — what True Cache removes from a standby setup

Physical Standby requires (extra steps)	True Cache — these steps are gone
•	RMAN DUPLICATE to seed all datafiles
•	Standby redo log creation on both hosts
•	ASM disk group sizing and provisioning
•	STARTUP NOMOUNT / MOUNT sequence
•	MRP process management
•	Separate app connection URL / pool for reads
•	RMAN backup jobs on standby	•	No RMAN step — buffer cache built lazily
•	No standby redo logs on either host
•	No disk storage to provision or manage
•	DBCA -createTrueCache does everything
•	No MRP — apply starts automatically
•	JDBC auto-routes — zero app changes
•	No backups — True Cache is stateless

Key takeaway: If you have built a Physical Standby before, you already know 60% of True Cache setup. The primary-side configuration is identical. True Cache removes the three most time-consuming standby tasks: RMAN restore, standby redo log creation, and manual MRP startup.

